1
00:00:01,667 --> 00:00:28,890
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sambha Sambhudassam Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sambha Sambhudassam Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sambha Sambhudassam

2
00:00:29,140 --> 00:00:34,765
homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-enlightened one.

3
00:00:34,786 --> 00:00:41,033
So we've now come to his advice to husbands and wives.

4
00:00:41,834 --> 00:00:46,999
I've chosen, there's a couple of discourses here, but I've chosen two of them.

5
00:00:48,341 --> 00:00:52,244
So the first one, he says, different kinds of marriages.

6
00:00:53,912 --> 00:01:03,506
On one occasion the Blessed One was travelling along the highway between Madura and Veranja, and a number of householders and their wives were travelling along the same road.

7
00:01:04,828 --> 00:01:13,480
Then the Blessed One left the road and sat down on a seat at the foot of a tree, and the householders and their wives saw the Blessed One sitting there, and approached him.

8
00:01:14,120 --> 00:01:23,093
And having paid homage to him, they sat down to one side, and the Blessed One said to them, Householders, there are four kinds of marriages.

9
00:01:24,067 --> 00:01:24,588
What for?

10
00:01:25,409 --> 00:01:27,370
A wretch lives with another wretch.

11
00:01:28,531 --> 00:01:30,334
A wretch lives together with a goddess.

12
00:01:31,254 --> 00:01:33,137
A god lives together with a wretch.

13
00:01:33,957 --> 00:01:36,319
And a god lives together with a goddess.

14
00:01:38,221 --> 00:01:40,844
And how does a wretch live together with a wretch?

15
00:01:41,745 --> 00:01:51,055
Hear, householders, the husband is one who destroys life, takes what is not given, engages in sexual misconduct, speaks falsely,

16
00:01:51,287 --> 00:01:55,492
and indulges in wines, liquors, and intoxicants, the basis for negligence.

17
00:01:56,674 --> 00:01:58,615
He is immoral, of bad character.

18
00:01:58,656 --> 00:02:03,120
He dwells at home with a heart obsessed by the stain of stinginess.

19
00:02:03,861 --> 00:02:09,848
He abuses and reviles ascetics and Brahmins, and his wife is exactly the same in all respects.

20
00:02:11,028 --> 00:02:14,513
And in such a way, a wretch lives together with a wretch.

21
00:02:16,054 --> 00:02:19,959
It's pretty clear, isn't it?

22
00:02:19,979 --> 00:02:20,299
So, the first...

23
00:02:20,768 --> 00:02:31,018
The thing about this is, just a little aside, is just to notice that he talks always about wines, liquor and intoxicants as the basis for negligence.

24
00:02:33,639 --> 00:02:34,360
So we'll just go through.

25
00:02:34,381 --> 00:02:36,082
I mean, it's just a combination of these two now.

26
00:02:36,122 --> 00:02:38,465
So how does a wretch live together with a goddess?

27
00:02:39,325 --> 00:02:50,015
So a husband is one who destroys life, etc., etc., abuses and reviles ascetics and Brahmins, but his wife is one who abstains from the destruction of life.

28
00:02:50,401 --> 00:03:05,224
It does all the opposite, so abstains from taking what is not freely given, abstains from sexual misconduct, abstains from speaking falsely, does not indulge in wines, liquor and toxicants, the basis of negligence.

29
00:03:06,026 --> 00:03:08,409
She is not immoral or of bad character.

30
00:03:08,430 --> 00:03:13,538
She dwells at home with a heart not obsessed by the stain of stinginess.

31
00:03:13,558 --> 00:03:16,223
She does not abuse and revile ascetics and Brahmins.

32
00:03:18,176 --> 00:03:23,223
The other little aside there is their relationship to ascetics and Brahmins.

33
00:03:25,067 --> 00:03:29,032
Obviously, there were people in those times who didn't like these loafers.

34
00:03:29,532 --> 00:03:34,501
The Buddha, in fact, there's one point where a Brahmin abrades him as being absolutely useless.

35
00:03:35,102 --> 00:03:37,465
He's walking around.

36
00:03:37,485 --> 00:03:38,546
The Buddha defended himself.

37
00:03:39,026 --> 00:03:41,390
We'll come to that maybe another time.

38
00:03:41,411 --> 00:03:45,096
So then, of course, the other combination is a god who lives with a wretch.

39
00:03:45,430 --> 00:03:47,771
And finally, a god who lives with a goddess.

40
00:03:47,912 --> 00:04:01,183
Now, when you read this, you realize that the Buddha, when he's talking about happiness, when he's talking about harmony, he's always on this level of morality, or ethics rather.

41
00:04:01,883 --> 00:04:10,110
So, he's never talking about somebody who's rich living with somebody who's poor, or somebody who's healthy living with somebody who's sick.

42
00:04:10,951 --> 00:04:14,215
You know, it's always about how you relate to people.

43
00:04:14,275 --> 00:04:15,336
So, ethics is

44
00:04:15,973 --> 00:04:28,168
is basically around our relationships, whatever our relationships are, whether in this case it's between a husband and wife, or between yourself and nature, or even a stone.

45
00:04:28,928 --> 00:04:30,310
So that's what ethics is about.

46
00:04:30,591 --> 00:04:43,406
And as far as the Buddha is concerned, happiness is based upon the way we relate to things, either wholesomely or unwholesomely, or skillfully or unskillfully.

47
00:04:43,427 --> 00:04:45,288
And his whole teaching is

48
00:04:45,471 --> 00:04:46,574
about that.

49
00:04:49,336 --> 00:04:55,805
In fact, the path to liberation is about purifying the heart.

50
00:04:55,826 --> 00:04:56,827
It's very simple, isn't it?

51
00:04:58,711 --> 00:05:00,293
In the Dhammapada he makes it very clear.

52
00:05:00,312 --> 00:05:04,177
He says, cease from evil, do good, purify the heart.

53
00:05:04,197 --> 00:05:05,720
This is the teaching of all the Buddhas.

54
00:05:06,601 --> 00:05:08,644
He drives it down to that sort of simplicity.

55
00:05:09,725 --> 00:05:14,752
How do we relate to the world around us?

56
00:05:15,290 --> 00:05:17,853
And if we get that right, then we'll be happy.

57
00:05:18,252 --> 00:05:19,394
We'll be gods and goddesses.

58
00:05:21,175 --> 00:05:26,661
So that's the first little thing.

59
00:05:26,682 --> 00:05:29,764
And I've got a little note here from Uncle Eddie.

60
00:05:29,785 --> 00:05:40,696
Uncle Eddie is an archaeologist, and he was taking people around Amarapura, which is the main ancient city in Sri Lanka.

61
00:05:41,476 --> 00:05:43,879
And he had these little jokes, and one of them was,

62
00:05:44,180 --> 00:06:13,291
in marriage there are three kinds of rings there's the engagement ring the marriage ring and suffering he's a killer he was very funny so now now this is where we sometimes are disappointed in the Buddha because we forget that he is a his personality and his character is a product of his time and place

63
00:06:13,576 --> 00:06:15,377
So we can't expect them to be postmodern.

64
00:06:16,019 --> 00:06:21,124
So there's a lovely discourse here on the seven kinds of wives.

65
00:06:21,723 --> 00:06:27,350
And after you've read it, of course, you can displace wife with husband and you get much the same thing.

66
00:06:28,370 --> 00:06:34,516
So on one occasion, the Blessed One was dwelling at Sarvati in Jeta's Grove, an Atapindika's monastery.

67
00:06:34,557 --> 00:06:38,942
And Atapindika, remember, was the very rich merchant who bought him his first monastery.

68
00:06:40,762 --> 00:06:46,947
In the morning the Blessed One dressed, took his bowl and robe, and went to an Adipindika's house, where he sat down in a seat prepared for him.

69
00:06:47,869 --> 00:06:57,778
On that occasion people in the house were making uproar and a racket, and the householder, an Adipindika, approached the Blessed One, paid homage to him, and sat down to one side.

70
00:06:57,858 --> 00:07:03,663
And the Blessed One then said to him, Who are people in your house making this uproar and racket, householder?

71
00:07:05,324 --> 00:07:07,427
One should think they were fishermen making a haul of fish.

72
00:07:08,848 --> 00:07:10,009
Then Venerable Sir,

73
00:07:10,225 --> 00:07:13,608
that venerable sir is our daughter-in-law Sujata.

74
00:07:14,228 --> 00:07:17,572
She is rich and has been brought here from a rich family.

75
00:07:18,112 --> 00:07:21,095
She does not obey her father-in-law or mother-in-law nor her husband.

76
00:07:21,555 --> 00:07:24,858
She does not even honour, respect, esteem and venerate the Blessed One.

77
00:07:26,259 --> 00:07:29,603
Then the Blessed One called the daughter-in-law Sujata saying, Come Sujata.

78
00:07:31,886 --> 00:07:33,247
Yes, venerable sir, she replied.

79
00:07:33,286 --> 00:07:36,250
She went to the Blessed One, paid homage to him and sat to one side.

80
00:07:37,495 --> 00:07:40,757
And the Blessed One said to her, There are seven kinds of wives, Sujata.

81
00:07:40,898 --> 00:07:41,358
What seven?

82
00:07:41,978 --> 00:07:52,108
One is a slayer, one is a thief, one is a tyrant, one is a mother, one is a sister, one like a friend, and one like a handmaiden.

83
00:07:52,749 --> 00:07:54,511
These are the seven kinds of wives.

84
00:07:55,130 --> 00:07:56,331
Now which of these seven are you?

85
00:07:58,673 --> 00:08:02,298
I do not understand in detail the meaning of the Blessed One's brief statement.

86
00:08:02,757 --> 00:08:06,961
It would be good, Venerable Sir, if the Blessed One would teach me the Dharma in such a way

87
00:08:07,211 --> 00:08:09,394
that I might understand the meaning in detail.

88
00:08:10,636 --> 00:08:14,581
And listen, Sujata, and attend carefully, and I will speak.

89
00:08:14,600 --> 00:08:29,899
Yes, venerable sir, Sujata replied, and the Blessed One said this, With hateful mind, cold and heartless, lusting for others, despising her husband, who seeks to kill the one who bought her, such a wife is called a slayer.

90
00:08:31,180 --> 00:08:36,746
Here's an interesting thing, that obviously in those days, the husband bought

91
00:08:37,267 --> 00:08:43,273
the wife from the family that she came from.

92
00:08:48,136 --> 00:08:58,866
When a husband acquires wealth by his craft or trade or farm work she tries to filch a little for herself such a wife is called a thief.

93
00:09:00,948 --> 00:09:05,653
The slothful glutton bent on idling harsh fierce roughing speech

94
00:09:05,971 --> 00:09:09,856
A woman who bullies her own supporter, such a wife is called a tyrant.

95
00:09:12,380 --> 00:09:20,152
One who is always helpful and kind, who guards a husband as a mother her son, who carefully protects the wealth he earns, such a wife is called a mother.

96
00:09:22,215 --> 00:09:31,489
She who holds her husband in high regard as a younger sister holds the elder born, who humbly submits to her husband's will, such a wife is called a sister.

97
00:09:31,789 --> 00:09:32,129
That's her.

98
00:09:32,296 --> 00:09:33,277
Stinger, isn't it, that one?

99
00:09:35,120 --> 00:09:36,761
It's not quite feminist, that one.

100
00:09:37,121 --> 00:09:39,725
I'll come back to that in a minute.

101
00:09:39,745 --> 00:09:47,796
One who rejoices at her husband's sight as a good friend might welcome another, well-raised, virtuous and devoted, such a wife is called a friend.

102
00:09:49,298 --> 00:09:58,809
One without anger, afraid of punishment, who bears with her husband free of hate, who humbly submits to her husband's will, such a wife is called a handmaid.

103
00:09:59,701 --> 00:10:05,086
These types of wives are called a slayer, a thief, the wife like a tyrant.

104
00:10:05,607 --> 00:10:10,232
These kinds of wives, with the body's breakup, will be reborn deep in hell.

105
00:10:11,774 --> 00:10:21,746
But wives like mother, like a mother, sister, friend, and a wife called a handmaid, steady in virtue, long restrained, with the body breakup, goes to heaven.

106
00:10:23,008 --> 00:10:25,530
These, Sujata, are the seven kinds of wives.

107
00:10:25,571 --> 00:10:26,592
Now, which of these are you?

108
00:10:27,573 --> 00:10:29,556
Beginning today, venerable sir,

109
00:10:29,822 --> 00:10:52,590
you should consider me as a wife like a handmaid so obviously we can we can change wife to husband and sort of go through it all the one here let's see what is it now oh dear dear dear

110
00:10:55,202 --> 00:11:00,291
Yes, I mean, there are things which don't ring so happily for us about obedience and all that.

111
00:11:01,572 --> 00:11:08,722
These days we presume equality and all that, a sense of negotiation.

112
00:11:11,466 --> 00:11:18,437
But all these qualities that he talks about are on either side, aren't they?

113
00:11:20,080 --> 00:11:22,003
He holds his wife in high esteem.

114
00:11:22,438 --> 00:11:31,086
as a younger brother holds his elder brother, rejoices at her sight, as one might welcome another.

115
00:11:32,407 --> 00:11:35,009
One without anger, afraid of punishment.

116
00:11:35,070 --> 00:11:37,892
That's a difficult one for us to get to.

117
00:11:38,832 --> 00:11:42,495
Afraid of being barked at, I suppose.

118
00:11:42,515 --> 00:11:44,577
Who bears his wife free of hate.

119
00:11:47,799 --> 00:11:52,024
So once you turn these things around,

120
00:11:52,341 --> 00:12:09,500
they have a sort of more general meaning for it one little thing that comes out here is this whole business of authority there's two things isn't there?

121
00:12:09,520 --> 00:12:21,133
there's being in authority over and an authority in so if you're in authority over then what you inspire is fear

122
00:12:21,568 --> 00:12:26,057
But if you're an authority in, then you inspire respect.

123
00:12:26,979 --> 00:12:39,120
So when you go to the doctor, generally speaking, we respect the person because we see them as an authority in their doctrine.

124
00:12:40,403 --> 00:12:44,091
But they don't have an authority over us.

125
00:12:44,110 --> 00:12:45,432
I remember once when...

126
00:12:45,869 --> 00:12:48,292
I had a bad cold, and I sort of went on and on and on.

127
00:12:49,232 --> 00:12:58,464
And I went to see my doctor, and he obviously knew that there were certain types of people that when you made a prescription, they didn't take it anyway.

128
00:12:59,304 --> 00:13:06,273
So it was funny, because he said to me, after he'd given me this prescription, he said, and make sure you take them.

129
00:13:06,293 --> 00:13:06,774
I said, what?

130
00:13:06,793 --> 00:13:07,134
How did he do it?

131
00:13:07,894 --> 00:13:11,479
Which of course I didn't, because it was only a cold for heaven's sake.

132
00:13:11,499 --> 00:13:14,643
He gave me antibacterial stuff.

133
00:13:14,663 --> 00:13:15,724
So...

134
00:13:16,615 --> 00:13:32,885
So the purpose of reading these things that the Buddha gives advice to lay people is that he is engaged in all the daily life and people went to him for what we would call just ordinary problems.

135
00:13:34,164 --> 00:13:41,736
And when you read the stuff, it's always around ethics and how we relate.

136
00:13:42,798 --> 00:13:47,846
Always around ethics and how we relate to people, to nature, to things.

137
00:13:49,307 --> 00:13:55,498
And that's what brings about, in his terms, a real sense of happiness, connectedness and all that.

138
00:13:58,229 --> 00:14:01,533
I can only hope my words have been of some assistance.

139
00:14:01,774 --> 00:14:14,634
May you be fully liberated from all suffering sooner rather than later, even if you're married.

